"West Clandon, Surrey, England","Rutland, England, United Kingdom":"Rutland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1380–1418":"1380–1418","1375–1400":"1375–1400","1377–1440":"1377–1440","1382–Female":"1382–Deceased","1384–Female":"1384–Deceased","1386–Female":"1386–Deceased","1380–1460":"1380–1460","1405–1466":"1405–1466","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1330–1418":"1330–1418","1356–1449":"1356–1449","1330":"1330","1440":"1440","1384":"1384","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Abt 1410":"about 1410","1356":"1356","1466":"1466","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1377":"1377","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","1405":"1405","1449":"1449","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Ockham, Surrey, England":"Ockham, Surrey, England","West Clandon, Surrey, England":"West Clandon, Surrey, England","Rutland, England, United Kingdom":"Rutland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Weston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of numerous places called Weston, from Old English <i>west</i> ‘west’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte west tun(e)</i> ‘at the west farmstead, settlement’ (Old English <i>west</i> + <i>tūn</i>), or from Middle English <i>(bi) weste(n)tune</i> (Old English <i>be westan tūne</i> or <i>be west in tūne</i>), denoting someone who lived either to the west of a settlement or in the western part of a settlement. The latter was a common surname in Sussex."],"variants":[{"name":"Wesson","meanings":["English (Midlands and Kent): variant of   Weston  .","History: John Wesson came from England to Salem, MA, in 1644."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Weston VI was born in 1380, in West Clandon, Surrey, England, his father, William De Weston V, was 50 and his mother, Joan Leghe, was 24. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Matilda Herrberger. In 1417, at the age of 37, his occupation is listed as high sheriff of surrey. H